{
  "texts": [
    "For fossil analysis, this non-invasive technique can be invaluable for revealing specimen internal structures (Garwood et al. 2010), with micro CT in particular revolutionizing the study of ancient life.",
    "Critically, fossils to be well-suited for tomographic imaging, the targeted specimen must exhibit sufficient contrast in X-ray attenuation compared to its surrounding matrix and cements, which cannot always be guaranteed.",
    "Moreover, preparing CT data for paleontology studies typically requires significant user intervention in terms of image processing and analysis, with the output image data commonly suffering significant noise, as well as potentially deleterious artefacts (especially beam hardening effects in the case of polychromatic lab and industrial sources), which can compromise data quality, impacting the performance of DL (McCollough et al. 2009; Chilamkurthy et al. 2018).",
    "And whilst the 3D datasets produced by X-ray computed tomography contain rich information for DL model training, the aggressive data volumes they present can be challenging to manage and integrate within DL studies, with limitations in terms of input image dimensions for common DL frameworks necessitating potentially deleterious downsampling of tomographic images.",
    "Finally, the 3D nature of X-ray tomography may present additional challenges, limiting the number of models available that can handle 3D arrays as training data."
  ]
}